04346nam a22005535i 9780228009306DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280093067 a10.1515/97802280093062doi  a(DE-B1597)655786  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPQ6351b.C37 2022 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a863/.32231 aCastillo, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat Would Cervantes Do? :bNavigating Post-Truth with Spanish Baroque Literature /cWilliam Egginton, David Castillo. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Iberian and Latin American Cultures Series ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tThe Deadly Devolution of Language -- tTrue Lies and Other Rules of Engagement -- tReality Entitlement -- tThe Imagination of the Possible -- tThe Art of the Real -- tThe Apocalypse Will Not Be Televised! -- tFrom Breaking Bad to Breaking Worse -- tPlaying the Game -- tHe Said, She Said -- tNot Your Father’s Classroom -- tThe Poison of Purity -- tHer Weapon -- tA Homeopathic Cure for Patriarchy -- tA Cervantine Toolkit for the Post-Truth Age -- tRevelations of a Glass Man -- tA Posthumous Lesson -- tSurviving the Post-Truth Age -- tLooking for Relevance in All the Right Places -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe attack on the US Capitol on 6 January 2021 was a tragic illustration of the existential threat that the viral spread of disinformation poses in the age of social media and twenty-four-hour news. From climate change denialism to the frenzied conspiracy theories and racist mythologies that fuel antidemocratic white nationalist movements in the United States and abroad, What Would Cervantes Do? is a lucid meditation on the key role the humanities must play in dissecting and combatting all forms of disinformation.David Castillo and William Egginton travel back to the early modern period, the first age of inflationary media, in search of historically tested strategies to overcome disinformation and shed light on our post-truth market. Through a series of critical conversations between cultural icons of the twenty-first century and those of the Spanish Golden Age, What Would Cervantes Do? provides a tour-de-force commentary on current politics and popular culture. Offering a diverse range of Cervantist comparative readings of contemporary cultural texts –movies, television shows, and infotainment – alongside ideas and issues from literary and cultural texts of early modern Spain, Castillo and Egginton present a new way of unpacking the logic of contemporary media.What Would Cervantes Do? is an urgent and timely self-help manual for literary scholars and humanists of all stripes, and a powerful toolkit for reality literacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDisinformation. 0aFake news. 0aInformation literacy. 0aMass mediaxObjectivity. 0aSpanish literatureyClassical period, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aTruthfulness and falsehood in literature. 0aTruthfulness and falsehood. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aEgginton, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800930640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228009306423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228009306/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles